comments.body:
One answer is that it would be annoying: this is probably something like
```go
docker.ErrUnauthorizedForCredentials{
  errcode.Error{
    Code: errcode.ErrorCodeUnauthorized,
    Message: "please use personal access token to login",
  }
}
```
i.e. the API-visible code is just “unauthorized” and we would have to special-case the exact string.

Another answer is that we are _already_ special-casing this: The server-provided text is dropped in (in this case, a past version of) https://github.com/containers/common/blob/ea87b34db578e5f4485b79d53125f20c3668a28a/pkg/auth/auth.go#L180 .

I think what we should do is to modify the special case logic in `auth.go` further, so that it is quite a bit smarter about what it strips, i.e. to parse the `unauthorized` value and only override the message if `unauthorized` contains the expected error type _and_ with the expected error message. I.e. switch from overriding everything, and possibly special-casing strings to preserve, to preserving everything, and special-casing redundant strings to simplify.

(I guess short-term that will lead to regressions from nice error messages to ugly error messages, as we re-add special cases. So, collecting exact error messages that we _do_ want to match, in test cases, similarly to https://github.com/containers/image/blob/main/docker/errors_test.go , seems valuable for long-term maintenance.)
